So gravity is so weak,
we're nowhere near

00:34:11.389 --> 00:34:13.389
the regime of probing
the quantum scale.

00:34:13.389 --> 00:34:16.600
AUDIENCE: What would the-- I
mean, we kind of understand

00:34:16.600 --> 00:34:21.575
the photon, how waves,
electromagnetic waves

00:34:21.575 --> 00:34:27.670
and photons can
be converted back

00:34:27.670 --> 00:34:29.510
and forth between each other.

00:34:29.510 --> 00:34:33.060
Theoretically, what would
the gravitational wave

00:34:33.060 --> 00:34:38.239
that they detected look
like for gravitons?

00:34:38.239 --> 00:34:41.400
JANNA LEVIN: You mean if we
could probe the quantum level?

00:34:41.400 --> 00:34:45.370
So the light in this room is
made up of so many photons

00:34:45.370 --> 00:34:49.110
that it's really hard to notice
the particulate nature of it.

00:34:49.110 --> 00:34:51.000
And similarly, the
gravitational waves

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:52.750
are made up of so many
gravitons that it's

00:34:52.750 --> 00:34:55.230
impossible to notice the
particulate nature of it.

00:34:55.230 --> 00:34:57.270
We haven't really
very well thought

00:34:57.270 --> 00:35:00.300
of an experiment where
we could do that.

00:35:00.300 --> 00:35:03.120
And probably, the energy
scale you'd have to get to

00:35:03.120 --> 00:35:11.710
is something like
a million times

00:35:11.710 --> 00:35:15.980
the Large Hadron Collider
energy, something like that.

00:35:15.980 --> 00:35:18.501
So it's not an ambition
of the near future.

00:35:18.501 --> 00:35:19.750
I mean, this was pretty crazy.

00:35:19.750 --> 00:35:21.650
But that would be really crazy.

00:35:21.650 --> 00:35:24.169
Yes?

00:35:24.169 --> 00:35:25.960
AUDIENCE: So it sounded
like-- I'm not sure

00:35:25.960 --> 00:35:26.730
if I understood correctly.

00:35:26.730 --> 00:35:28.250
But part of the
reason your software

00:35:28.250 --> 00:35:30.422
was able to detect this
event and notify you guys--

00:35:30.422 --> 00:35:32.630
because you kind of knew
what you were listening for.

00:35:32.630 --> 00:35:34.690
You kind of had a prediction
for what it would sound like.

00:35:34.690 --> 00:35:34.955
JANNA LEVIN: Yeah.

00:35:34.955 --> 00:35:35.670
AUDIENCE: Is that correct?

00:35:35.670 --> 00:35:37.128
JANNA LEVIN: Well,
that is correct.

00:35:37.128 --> 00:35:38.880
One of the difficulties
in this experiment

00:35:38.880 --> 00:35:42.910
is that the sound will often
be quieter than the noise.

00:35:42.910 --> 00:35:49.020
And so they'll have to sometimes
run the predictions, especially

00:35:49.020 --> 00:35:52.580
the numerical ones, in through
the data and filter it that way

00:35:52.580 --> 00:35:53.330
and pluck it out.

00:35:53.330 --> 00:35:57.220
But this one was so loud, it's
just right above the noise.

00:35:57.220 --> 00:35:58.850
It's actually really loud.

00:35:58.850 --> 00:36:02.690
So it's not as reliant
on that as we fully

00:36:02.690 --> 00:36:04.400
expected things to be.

00:36:04.400 --> 00:36:05.970
AUDIENCE: So is it that you
guys are actually just running

00:36:05.970 --> 00:36:07.230
straight up anomaly detection?

00:36:07.230 --> 00:36:09.400
And that's what you want
to use to possibly detect

00:36:09.400 --> 00:36:10.660
other events in the future?

00:36:10.660 --> 00:36:11.769
JANNA LEVIN: Yeah.

00:36:11.769 --> 00:36:13.310
There's three or
four different teams

00:36:13.310 --> 00:36:16.499
within the collaboration that
use different models to pluck

00:36:16.499 --> 00:36:17.790
out different kinds of signals.

00:36:17.790 --> 00:36:18.950
Some are burst signals.

00:36:18.950 --> 00:36:21.970
Some are these-- what we call
compact binary coalescence,

00:36:21.970 --> 00:36:25.040
things like black holes and
neutron stars and white dwarfs.

00:36:25.040 --> 00:36:29.327
And some stochastic,
which is just noisier.

00:36:29.327 --> 00:36:31.160
So there's all of these
different algorithms

00:36:31.160 --> 00:36:31.880
that people write.

00:36:31.880 --> 00:36:33.260
But I don't think
anyone expected

00:36:33.260 --> 00:36:36.690
the first signal we detect
to be just noticeably loud.

00:36:36.690 --> 00:36:37.190
Yeah.

00:36:37.190 --> 00:36:37.660
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:36:37.660 --> 00:36:38.770
JANNA LEVIN: Sure.

00:36:38.770 --> 00:36:39.890
It was just fast.

00:36:39.890 --> 00:36:43.180
If it had been slower, I
think they would have heard it

00:36:43.180 --> 00:36:44.470
in the control room.

00:36:44.470 --> 00:36:45.969
It was that loud.

00:36:45.969 --> 00:36:47.510
AUDIENCE: What is
the range of events

00:36:47.510 --> 00:36:49.634
that you expect to be
able to detect with LIGO?

00:36:49.634 --> 00:36:51.050
I understand there
are [INAUDIBLE]

00:36:51.050 --> 00:36:54.240
like solar-system scale
interferometers for detecting

00:36:54.240 --> 00:36:56.440
less energetic events or
more energetic events.

00:36:56.440 --> 00:36:57.231
JANNA LEVIN: Right.

00:36:57.231 --> 00:37:00.580
So the scale-- so
it happens that LIGO

00:37:00.580 --> 00:37:04.470
is sensitive to the
human auditory range.

00:37:04.470 --> 00:37:08.130
And that's just
strange, coincidence.

00:37:08.130 --> 00:37:11.100
But these black holes
about this size, that's

00:37:11.100 --> 00:37:13.060
the natural frequency
at which they

00:37:13.060 --> 00:37:14.352
would emit gravitational waves.

00:37:14.352 --> 00:37:16.726
But I think when they designed
the instrument-- you know,

00:37:16.726 --> 00:37:18.270
this has been going
on for 50 years.

00:37:18.270 --> 00:37:19.890
They were looking for supernova.

00:37:19.890 --> 00:37:22.720
They were hoping to
hear things like that.

00:37:22.720 --> 00:37:25.010
So it turns out that
the supernova might

00:37:25.010 --> 00:37:27.500
be too quiet or too
difficult And that these

00:37:27.500 --> 00:37:29.950
are much more populous.

00:37:29.950 --> 00:37:33.424
And but yes, if you send
something in space--

00:37:33.424 --> 00:37:35.090
and there is a project
to send something

00:37:35.090 --> 00:37:37.410
into space-- millions
of kilometers apart,

00:37:37.410 --> 00:37:40.460
they would be way outside
of the human auditory range,

00:37:40.460 --> 00:37:42.300
way lower in frequency.

00:37:42.300 --> 00:37:43.830
And they would be
detecting things

00:37:43.830 --> 00:37:47.380
like supermassive black holes
colliding, bigger things, lower

00:37:47.380 --> 00:37:49.400
frequency stuff.

00:37:49.400 --> 00:37:49.929
Yes?

00:37:49.929 --> 00:37:50.470
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:37:50.470 --> 00:37:51.010
JANNA LEVIN: Hi.

00:37:51.010 --> 00:37:52.274
AUDIENCE: How
close would we have

00:37:52.274 --> 00:37:54.148
had to have been to the
colliding black holes

00:37:54.148 --> 00:37:57.980
for them to kill us with
gravitational force.

00:37:57.980 --> 00:38:00.790
JANNA LEVIN: That's an
interesting question.

00:38:00.790 --> 00:38:03.790
It would be pretty hard to kill
us with gravitational waves.

00:38:03.790 --> 00:38:04.720
They're so weak.

00:38:04.720 --> 00:38:05.940
It would be really hard.

00:38:05.940 --> 00:38:09.280
Like, to be squeezed
and stretched

00:38:09.280 --> 00:38:15.170
like-- with your bare hands,
you could squeeze and stretch

00:38:15.170 --> 00:38:17.300
me billions of
trillions of times

00:38:17.300 --> 00:38:19.840
harder than a
gravitational wave could.

00:38:19.840 --> 00:38:24.570
So I think I'd be much more
worried just about being

00:38:24.570 --> 00:38:28.017
near the black holes generally.

00:38:28.017 --> 00:38:30.350
But black holes aren't really
the engines of destruction

00:38:30.350 --> 00:38:31.600
that they are portrayed to be.

00:38:31.600 --> 00:38:34.560
If our sun was replaced
with a black hole tomorrow,

00:38:34.560 --> 00:38:37.300
we wouldn't get sucked in like
a vacuum cleaner would suck us

00:38:37.300 --> 00:38:37.810
in.

00:38:37.810 --> 00:38:39.170
We would actually
orbit just fine.

00:38:39.170 --> 00:38:40.690
The orbit would be
exactly the same.

00:38:40.690 --> 00:38:42.050
It would be totally fine.

00:38:42.050 --> 00:38:45.680
I mean, we'd be dead because
it would be cold and dark.

00:38:45.680 --> 00:38:47.850
But we wouldn't fall in.

00:38:47.850 --> 00:38:51.155
And we were actually very slowly
falling into a black hole now.

00:38:51.155 --> 00:38:52.530
There's a supermassive
black hole

00:38:52.530 --> 00:38:54.761
at the center of our galaxy
4 million times the mass

00:38:54.761 --> 00:38:55.260
of the sun.

00:38:55.260 --> 00:38:57.343
And we are, in fact, falling
into that black hole.

00:38:57.343 --> 00:39:01.420
It's going to take a very
long time, very long time.

00:39:01.420 --> 00:39:04.650
I really am worried
about other things.

00:39:04.650 --> 00:39:05.430
Yeah?

00:39:05.430 --> 00:39:07.679
AUDIENCE: If you had an
infinitely sensitive detector,

00:39:07.679 --> 00:39:09.679
where would you see
gravitational waves from?

00:39:09.679 --> 00:39:10.845
Would it be from everything?

00:39:10.845 --> 00:39:11.880
Or is it just--

00:39:11.880 --> 00:39:12.880
JANNA LEVIN: Everything.

00:39:12.880 --> 00:39:15.410
I would make gravitational
waves right now.

00:39:15.410 --> 00:39:19.030
Infinitely sensitive
detector would pick up

00:39:19.030 --> 00:39:21.820
gravitational waves from
all of us moving around.

00:39:21.820 --> 00:39:22.320
And--

00:39:22.320 --> 00:39:23.779
AUDIENCE: So you
have to be moving.

00:39:23.779 --> 00:39:25.236
JANNA LEVIN: You
have to be moving.

00:39:25.236 --> 00:39:27.160
So a black hole
just sitting there

00:39:27.160 --> 00:39:29.890
is not going to create
gravitational waves.

00:39:29.890 --> 00:39:33.320
And it's just a funny
thing, that if, like,

00:39:33.320 --> 00:39:35.774
a star exploded
perfectly symmetrically

00:39:35.774 --> 00:39:37.440
in all directions,
it actually would not

00:39:37.440 --> 00:39:39.120
create gravitational waves.

00:39:39.120 --> 00:39:42.260
So you need what's called a
quadripolar or a certain kind

00:39:42.260 --> 00:39:45.040
of asymmetry and
accelerations of masses.

00:39:45.040 --> 00:39:45.550
Yeah.

00:39:45.550 --> 00:39:48.480
But I'm not
spherically symmetric.

00:39:48.480 --> 00:39:52.160
So I am making
gravitational waves.

00:39:52.160 --> 00:39:54.295
AUDIENCE: About the one
that [INAUDIBLE] I'm

00:39:54.295 --> 00:39:56.770
curious about what we
can know about them--

00:39:56.770 --> 00:39:58.143
their relative size?

00:39:58.143 --> 00:39:59.768
JANNA LEVIN: The
black holes, you mean?

00:39:59.768 --> 00:40:01.790
AUDIENCE: Yeah, the
one that we have.

00:40:01.790 --> 00:40:02.540
JANNA LEVIN: Yeah.

00:40:02.540 --> 00:40:04.490
AUDIENCE: --the sound.

00:40:04.490 --> 00:40:05.657
What can we know about them?

00:40:05.657 --> 00:40:06.406
JANNA LEVIN: Yeah.

00:40:06.406 --> 00:40:07.470
It's pretty amazing.

00:40:07.470 --> 00:40:09.850
So the details that we
seem to be able to extract

00:40:09.850 --> 00:40:13.280
is one was about 29 times the
mass of the sun to begin with.

00:40:13.280 --> 00:40:15.930
One was over 30.

00:40:15.930 --> 00:40:18.730
By the time they collided,
they made a black hole maybe

00:40:18.730 --> 00:40:21.840
about 62 times the
mass of the sun, which

00:40:21.840 --> 00:40:26.720
means some of the energy
that we call E = mc2 energy

00:40:26.720 --> 00:40:28.480
was emitted in the
gravitational waves.

00:40:28.480 --> 00:40:30.826
A few percent of the
energy was emitted

00:40:30.826 --> 00:40:31.950
in the gravitational waves.

00:40:31.950 --> 00:40:34.200
And that's a tremendous
amount of energy.

00:40:34.200 --> 00:40:37.360
That's just a huge
amount of energy.

00:40:37.360 --> 00:40:41.240
And that black hole is out
there right now, spinning.

00:40:41.240 --> 00:40:43.960
They think they know it's
spinning very rapidly, probably

00:40:43.960 --> 00:40:45.650
hundreds of times a second.

00:40:45.650 --> 00:40:48.700
We saw the last
four orbits or so.

00:40:48.700 --> 00:40:50.765
AUDIENCE: But that--
we know the location

00:40:50.765 --> 00:40:52.130
now of this black hole?

00:40:52.130 --> 00:40:53.510
JANNA LEVIN: Not very well.

00:40:53.510 --> 00:40:54.610
Not very well.

00:40:54.610 --> 00:40:57.720
It came from the southern
sky, somewhere over there.

00:40:57.720 --> 00:41:00.740
They have a map, a
kind of a splotchy map.

00:41:00.740 --> 00:41:02.380
It sort of came from over there.

00:41:02.380 --> 00:41:04.075
It's 1.3 billion years away.

00:41:04.075 --> 00:41:06.490
AUDIENCE: Are they
trying to find it?

00:41:06.490 --> 00:41:08.280
JANNA LEVIN: They
can't find it anymore

00:41:08.280 --> 00:41:11.310
because a telescope
can't see a dark object.

00:41:11.310 --> 00:41:15.160
And so what they could try
to do is pinpoint the galaxy

00:41:15.160 --> 00:41:16.480
that it lives in.

00:41:16.480 --> 00:41:18.587
And then that
would tell it how--

00:41:18.587 --> 00:41:20.670
something about the galaxy
might tell us something

00:41:20.670 --> 00:41:21.660
about the black holes.

00:41:21.660 --> 00:41:23.562
Very surprised that
they were that big.

00:41:23.562 --> 00:41:25.270
That was something
that surprised people.

00:41:25.270 --> 00:41:26.900
I wasn't particularly surprised.

00:41:26.900 --> 00:41:31.040
I work on this a
lot, and I never

00:41:31.040 --> 00:41:34.290
had a prejudice against
big black holes.

00:41:34.290 --> 00:41:35.350
But a lot of people did.

00:41:35.350 --> 00:41:37.240
They just thought it'll
be hard to make 'em.

00:41:37.240 --> 00:41:40.730
But we-- the details of how to
make black holes is so hard,

00:41:40.730 --> 00:41:43.230
I always thought, we're
probably not right about a lot

00:41:43.230 --> 00:41:44.520
of that stuff.

00:41:44.520 --> 00:41:46.789
So this was real
astronomical information

00:41:46.789 --> 00:41:47.830
from the first detection.

00:41:47.830 --> 00:41:51.220
It wasn't just we recorded
gravitational waves.

00:41:51.220 --> 00:41:54.990
It was we've discovered the
first black-hole system,

00:41:54.990 --> 00:41:58.070
and we've discovered the first
collision of black holes.

00:41:58.070 --> 00:42:01.570
And we know things that
we didn't know before.

00:42:01.570 --> 00:42:02.380
It's very cool.

00:42:02.380 --> 00:42:05.630
They were very
lucky, very lucky.

00:42:05.630 --> 00:42:06.780
Yes?

00:42:06.780 --> 00:42:11.890
AUDIENCE: What other
gravitational wave detection

00:42:11.890 --> 00:42:13.650
systems are coming online soon?

00:42:13.650 --> 00:42:14.400
JANNA LEVIN: Yeah.

00:42:14.400 --> 00:42:16.935
So there is this one
called KAGRA, which

00:42:16.935 --> 00:42:18.060
is going to be underground.

00:42:18.060 --> 00:42:20.030
And that helps isolate
it seismically.

00:42:20.030 --> 00:42:21.620
So that will be helpful.

00:42:21.620 --> 00:42:24.180
At some level, the
experiments are limited just

00:42:24.180 --> 00:42:25.764
by quantum noise,
that there's nothing

00:42:25.764 --> 00:42:27.638
you can do about quantum
mechanics, you know,

00:42:27.638 --> 00:42:28.830
quantum fluctuations.

00:42:28.830 --> 00:42:31.640
If you've heard about
Heisenberg's uncertainty

00:42:31.640 --> 00:42:33.980
principle, it makes
it impossible.

00:42:33.980 --> 00:42:37.860
In some regime, they're working
on suppressing quantum effects.

00:42:37.860 --> 00:42:40.800
But eventually, they'll hit
some fundamental physical limit

00:42:40.800 --> 00:42:44.810
where the Heisenberg uncertainty
principle says you can never

00:42:44.810 --> 00:42:47.590
precisely locate an object.

00:42:47.590 --> 00:42:50.110
And they'll be up against
that limit with the mirrors.

00:42:50.110 --> 00:42:50.620
Right?

00:42:50.620 --> 00:42:53.980
It's just-- it doesn't exist
in a precise enough location

00:42:53.980 --> 00:42:57.240
anymore, technically.

00:42:57.240 --> 00:42:59.470
But KAGRA will help
with seismic stuff.

00:42:59.470 --> 00:43:02.910
And there's VIRGO which is an
Italy, which will hopefully

00:43:02.910 --> 00:43:05.257
come online in the
summer, as well.

00:43:05.257 --> 00:43:06.840
And then I mentioned
the one in India.

00:43:06.840 --> 00:43:08.950
And there's GEO.

00:43:08.950 --> 00:43:11.790
And I can't remember all
of the others right now.

00:43:11.790 --> 00:43:14.120
TAMA, I think, is offline now.

00:43:14.120 --> 00:43:16.180
But there's a whole
network of them.

00:43:16.180 --> 00:43:19.220
Eventually in space-- that
would be very exciting.

00:43:19.220 --> 00:43:21.220
Do you mean just gravitational
wave, by the way?

00:43:21.220 --> 00:43:23.570
Or any gravity experiments?

00:43:23.570 --> 00:43:25.020
AUDIENCE: Gravity waves.

00:43:25.020 --> 00:43:25.770
JANNA LEVIN: Yeah.

00:43:25.770 --> 00:43:26.740
So these are the ones.

00:43:26.740 --> 00:43:28.510
They're are all of
the LIGO variety,

00:43:28.510 --> 00:43:31.950
except the space-borne
LISA, which

00:43:31.950 --> 00:43:35.860
would put three spacecraft,
disconnected, millions

00:43:35.860 --> 00:43:37.490
of kilometers apart
from each other,

00:43:37.490 --> 00:43:40.267
freely floating in space for
gravitational wave passes.

00:43:40.267 --> 00:43:41.850
They all just bob,
and they keep track

00:43:41.850 --> 00:43:43.510
of each other with a laser.

00:43:43.510 --> 00:43:45.282
It's a really clever experiment.

00:43:45.282 --> 00:43:47.740
There are some people who are
trying different ideas, again

00:43:47.740 --> 00:43:49.990
going back to atomic clocks
and timing experiments.

00:43:49.990 --> 00:43:51.850
But, you know, they're very new.

00:43:51.850 --> 00:43:54.440
So it would be interesting to
see if anyone makes progress

00:43:54.440 --> 00:43:57.260
with that.

00:43:57.260 --> 00:44:00.604
I put the clock at--
we're counting down to 1.

00:44:00.604 --> 00:44:02.020
But I think we
could take one more

00:44:02.020 --> 00:44:04.080
question if somebody wanted to.

00:44:04.080 --> 00:44:04.820
Yeah?

00:44:04.820 --> 00:44:07.110
Or two more.

00:44:07.110 --> 00:44:08.610
Yes.

00:44:08.610 --> 00:44:12.048
AUDIENCE: So I was thinking
about the earlier question

00:44:12.048 --> 00:44:13.047
about the gravity waves.

00:44:13.047 --> 00:44:14.990
So they were formed
by the black holes.

00:44:14.990 --> 00:44:15.640
They came by.

00:44:15.640 --> 00:44:16.431
They were detected.

00:44:16.431 --> 00:44:20.300
And as they spread out,
they get weaker and weaker.

00:44:20.300 --> 00:44:23.180
So they don't really dissipate
because there's no friction.

00:44:23.180 --> 00:44:25.150
So what happens to them?

00:44:25.150 --> 00:44:26.510
They just keep going on forever?

00:44:26.510 --> 00:44:29.560
JANNA LEVIN: Well, just
imagine a light bulb up close

00:44:29.560 --> 00:44:30.440
is very bright.

00:44:30.440 --> 00:44:31.734
And far away, it's very dim.

00:44:31.734 --> 00:44:34.150
And it's just cause you're
really intercepting less of it,

00:44:34.150 --> 00:44:35.010
to some extent.

00:44:35.010 --> 00:44:35.510
Right?

00:44:35.510 --> 00:44:36.860
You're up close,
you're intercepting

00:44:36.860 --> 00:44:38.010
a whole lot of the light.

00:44:38.010 --> 00:44:39.170
But if it's very
far away, you're

00:44:39.170 --> 00:44:40.253
getting very little of it.

